  "footnotes": [
    "Srivijaya (c.650–1025): a Malay Buddhist thalassocracy based in Sumatra that dominated the Strait of Malacca and controlled maritime trade between China and India; its influence extended across the Malay Peninsula and Borneo coast; Chola naval raids from India fatally weakened it in 1025",
    "Malacca Sultanate (1400–1511): founded by Parameswara (a Srivijayan prince), Malacca became the greatest entrepôt in Southeast Asia and the primary vector for Islamization of the Malay world; its capture by the Portuguese in 1511 disrupted but did not destroy Malay Muslim political culture — successor sultanates (Johor, Perak, Pahang) carried on the tradition",
    "Brunei Sultanate: at its peak in the 15th–16th centuries, Brunei controlled most of coastal Borneo and parts of the Philippines (Sulu, Manila); European colonialism and the Brooke dynasty in Sarawak gradually reduced it to its present tiny territory; the discovery of oil (1929) transformed it into one of the world's wealthiest states per capita",
    "White Rajahs of Sarawak (1841–1946): James Brooke, a British adventurer, was granted Sarawak by the Sultan of Brunei for suppressing a rebellion; the Brooke family ruled as personal monarchs for three generations — one of the most unusual colonial arrangements in history; Sarawak became a Crown Colony in 1946",
    "Malayan Emergency (1948–1960): a communist insurgency led predominantly by ethnic Chinese guerrillas; the British and Malayan forces defeated it through a combination of military operations and winning Malay 'hearts and minds' (the Briggs Plan); the Emergency shaped Malaysia's ethnic politics and security outlook for decades",
    "Singapore's expulsion (1965): Singapore was expelled from the Malaysian federation after political tensions between the PAP (Lee Kuan Yew) and UMNO over racial policies and economic vision; Lee famously wept at the press conference; the tiny city-state subsequently built one of the world's most successful economies through export-oriented industrialization and strict governance",
    "Malaysian federation (1963): the merger of Malaya, Singapore, Sarawak, and North Borneo (Sabah) was partly motivated by fear of communist expansion and the need to balance Singapore's Chinese majority with Borneo's indigenous populations; Brunei declined to join, partly due to disputes over oil revenues and the sultan's political status"
  ]
}
